    <p class="kicker">Institutional Documentation</p>
    <h1>Governance</h1>

    <p>
      The Library is the public-facing work of two affiliated nonprofits. This page names the people who run it today, the bodies that will share that work as the Library matures, and the rules under which decisions get made. Governance pages exist so that readers — patrons, contributors, journalists, and the public agencies the Library covers — can see who is responsible for what the Library says.
    </p>

    <h2>Sponsorship and lifecycle</h2>

    <p>
      America's School Trust Library is a joint project of two 501(c)(3) nonprofits.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Oregon Advocates for School Trust Lands (OASTL)</strong> is the host. OASTL is ASTL's Oregon affiliate, the active plaintiff in <em>Advocates for School Trust Lands v. State of Oregon</em> (Oregon Court of Appeals standing victory, January 28, 2026), and the Library's fiscal home. Day-to-day operating decisions sit with OASTL.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Advocates for School Trust Lands (ASTL)</strong> is the national co-sponsor. ASTL contributes national scope, per-state field reporting, and the substantive review that keeps the Library's coverage credible outside Oregon.
    </p>

    <p>
      The Library is OASTL's flagship initiative today. It is designed to spin out into its own independent 501(c)(3) when patron support, contributor breadth, and operating scope reach the point where independence is the better structure. The trigger conditions are named below.
    </p>

    <h2>Today's officers</h2>

    <p>
      The Library has two named founding officers and a small editorial staff. The public stewardship ledger lives at <a href="/the-watchful-crew/">/the-watchful-crew/</a>.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Dave Sullivan — President, OASTL.</strong> Founder of the Library; decisional lead on editorial direction; architect of the Library's substrate. Retired professor and lead plaintiff in OASTL's Oregon litigation.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Margaret Bird — President, ASTL.</strong> Co-founder of the Library; co-author of <em>Schools of the Republic</em>; national authority on school trust law. Substantive review of all national-scope content.
    </p>

    <p>
      Editorial work is supported by AI assistance under the supervision of the named founders. Methodology is described at <a href="/about/how-this-works/">/about/how-this-works/</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>The Library Board (planned)</h2>

    <p>
      A standing Library Board will provide editorial guidance, archival discipline, and the institutional memory of how a library posture differs from an advocacy posture. The Board is separate from the operating boards of OASTL and ASTL: the sponsoring organizations run advocacy and litigation; the Library Board runs the Library.
    </p>

    <p>
      The first cohort is expected to be three to five members, drawn from library science, archives, and digital-library infrastructure. Initial terms will be three years, staggered, with one renewal permitted. Seats will be filled by appointment of the two sponsoring presidents from a public call for applications; the application process opens once the first seat is funded for staff support. The Board is expected to convene quarterly with minutes published on this site.
    </p>

    <p>
      Until the Board is seated, its functions sit with the two founding officers and are recorded as such.
    </p>

    <h2>State Co-Librarians (applications open)</h2>

    <p>
      A State Co-Librarian is the named curator of one state's pages — typically the State Records page, the state's Counting House entry, and the state-specific source pages in the Reading Room. The role does not require leaving an existing job: most State Co-Librarians are expected to be current or recent staff of State Departments of Lands, State Treasurers' offices, school-finance offices, or state historical societies, contributing in their professional capacity. Where participation under a real name would be professionally costly, a verified pseudonym is available and verification is held confidentially by the founding officers (and, once seated, the Library Board).
    </p>

    <p>
      Responsibilities: validate the figures and history the Library publishes about that state; supply primary sources the Library is missing; flag errors and supervise their correction; review changes before they go live; carry the institutional memory of the state's trust into the Library's record.
    </p>

    <p>
      <strong>Applications are open.</strong> Apply at <a href="/apply/state-co-librarian/">/apply/state-co-librarian/</a>. Conversations with individual prospective co-librarians are already underway, and applications will be reviewed by the two founding officers as they come in. The <strong>NASTL conference, July 2026</strong>, is the first public recruitment event — a venue where the Library will name the role from the stage and meet candidates in person — but the sign-up path is open now. Filling the first ten state seats is the goal for the twelve months ahead.
    </p>

    <h2>Co-Librarian (express interest open)</h2>

    <p>
      A Co-Librarian is a senior curator with cross-state authority on doctrinal questions or topical specialties — trust-law doctrine, financial accounting, federal-policy history, archival method. Seats are a small number and currently fill by invitation, but the Library welcomes expressions of interest from people who think the role describes them. Use the Express Interest path linked from <a href="/pro/roles/">/pro/roles/</a>; replies come directly from the founding officers.
    </p>

    <h2>The broader community of contributors</h2>

    <p>
      Beyond the Board and the co-librarians, the Library depends on a wider community: historians, journalists, school-finance officers, retired educators, attorneys, parents, school-board members, and citizens who watch their state's trust administration. Participation today is open to anyone with a free Library Card and runs through in-product channels: source suggestions, error reports, annotations on Reading Room pages, and the contribution paths laid out at <a href="/about/contributing/">/about/contributing/</a>. Accepted contributions are credited on the pages they shape.
    </p>

    <p>
      For the role-by-role description of how contributors fit into the Library's work, see <a href="/pro/roles/">/pro/roles/</a>.
    </p>

    <h2>Editorial independence and the path to independence</h2>

    <p>
      The Library publishes under its own editorial judgment. OASTL hosts the Library; OASTL does not approve individual editorial decisions. Where the Library's record bears on OASTL's own litigation — most notably the Oregon case — the Library reports the same record it would report for any other state, and the bibliographic and citation rules in <a href="/about/cite/">/about/cite/</a> apply equally to OASTL's own filings.
    </p>

    <p>
      The Library is designed to outgrow OASTL's host capacity. The planned transition to an independent 501(c)(3) is expected when the following conditions are met:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>The Library Board is seated and has served at least one full term.</li>
      <li>Patron support reaches roughly 5,000 active Library Card holders.</li>
      <li>The community of recognized contributors reaches roughly 50, with at least 25 states represented.</li>
      <li>Operating budget reaches a level that supports at least one full-time librarian.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      Until those thresholds are met, OASTL hosting is the right structure. The trigger conditions are public so that patrons, contributors, and prospective Board members can see what independence depends on.
    </p>

    <h2>Decisions and disputes</h2>

    <p>
      Editorial decisions today are made by the two founding officers, with substantive review by Margaret Bird on national-scope content and by Dave Sullivan on Oregon-scope content. When the Library Board is seated, editorial-policy disputes — what to publish, how to characterize contested findings, when to retract — will rise to the Board.
    </p>

    <p>
      Factual corrections follow a separate path. A reader who believes the Library has a fact wrong files a correction (see <a href="/about/cite/">/about/cite/</a> for the address). Corrections are reviewed by the responsible librarian, applied to the source page, and logged. Disputed corrections, and any correction that touches an active legal matter, are reviewed by both founding officers before resolution. A fuller dispute-resolution procedure is in development and will be posted at <a href="/pro/dispute-resolution/">/pro/dispute-resolution/</a> when the Library Board is seated.
    </p>

    <h2>How to engage</h2>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Write to the Board.</strong> Until the Board is seated, correspondence intended for the Library's governance reaches both founding officers via the contact addresses at <a href="/about/">/about/</a>.</li>
      <li><strong>Apply for a Library Board seat.</strong> A public call will open once the first seat is funded for staff support. Watch <a href="/updates/">/updates/</a> for the announcement.</li>
      <li><strong>Become a State Co-Librarian.</strong> Reach out via the Library Card system or in person at the NASTL conference in July 2026.</li>
      <li><strong>Contribute.</strong> The on-ramp for everyone else is at <a href="/about/contributing/">/about/contributing/</a>.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      For the Library's editorial rules see <a href="/pro/editorial-standards/">/pro/editorial-standards/</a>. For what the Library collects and what it does not, see <a href="/pro/collection-development/">/pro/collection-development/</a>. For the Library's working methodology and substrate, see <a href="/about/how-this-works/">/about/how-this-works/</a>.
    </p>
